    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "5c7606c9_b55e89bb",
        "filename": "src/android/SkAnimatedImage.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 363,
      "author": {
        "id": 5255
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-01-08T14:44:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The bitmap is always going to be mutable, because we reuse it for the next frame, so this is essentially \"always copy\".\n\nThat said, SkAnimatedImage tries to be smart about this - it only reuses the pixel ref if it is unique. Otherwise it lazily does a copy. So I think you want to use kNever_SkCopyPixelsMode, perhaps with a comment that says something like:\n\n    // This SkBitmap may be reused later to decode the following frame. But Frame::init\n    // lazily copies the pixel ref if it has any other references. So it is safe to not\n    // do a deep copy here.\n\n(We already use kNever_SkCopyPixelsMode in onDraw. It does not have an analogous comment, but the same idea applies.)",
      "parentUuid": "fb500fb1_78fa21f6",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 363,
        "startChar": 39,
        "endLine": 363,
        "endChar": 66
      },
